WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.770 --> 00:00:02.280
Prof: Good morning.
 

00:00:02.280 --> 00:00:07.061
Now we move to our last author
in this course,

00:00:07.061 --> 00:00:09.930
to Émile Durkheim.
 

00:00:09.930 --> 00:00:14.970
There are really two Durkheims.
 

00:00:14.970 --> 00:00:21.900
We have seen certainly two
Marxs and two Webers.

00:00:21.900 --> 00:00:25.680
There are also two faces of
Émile Durkheim.

00:00:25.680 --> 00:00:32.289
To put it bluntly,
the young Durkheim has been a

00:00:32.289 --> 00:00:40.565
functionalist and a positivist,
and then late in his life he

00:00:40.565 --> 00:00:47.200
has--his epistemological turn--
he became a cultural analyst.

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:51.627
Well it's not quite true,
because each author is more

00:00:51.627 --> 00:00:56.822
complex, and there were already
elements of his culturalism in

00:00:56.822 --> 00:00:58.440
the early work.
 

00:00:58.440 --> 00:01:03.899
But there was certainly a
dramatic change in the way how

00:01:03.899 --> 00:01:09.260
Durkheim conceived what the job
of social sciences,

00:01:09.260 --> 00:01:13.183
later in his life,
in his book The Elementary

00:01:13.183 --> 00:01:15.688
Forms of Religious Life.
 

00:01:15.688 --> 00:01:19.727
I think it had a lot to do also
with his personal life,

00:01:19.727 --> 00:01:21.970
and we will talk about this.
 

00:01:21.970 --> 00:01:26.388
He was brought up in a
rabbinical family and was

00:01:26.388 --> 00:01:31.444
supposed to become a rabbi,
and then he revolted against

00:01:31.444 --> 00:01:36.379
the parental household--
much like Nietzsche did--and

00:01:36.379 --> 00:01:42.221
turned probably into an atheist,
but certainly not an active

00:01:42.221 --> 00:01:43.989
believer in Judaism.
 

00:01:43.989 --> 00:01:49.703
And later in his life he became
again interested in religion,

00:01:49.703 --> 00:01:54.559
and not only philosophically,
but also existentially

00:01:54.559 --> 00:01:57.129
interested in religion.
 

00:01:57.129 --> 00:02:03.239
Well in the course we have only
four lectures on Durkheim.

00:02:03.239 --> 00:02:07.340
So I'll leave Durkheim the
culturalist out,

00:02:07.340 --> 00:02:13.080
and we will be doing work only
on his earlier work,

00:02:13.080 --> 00:02:18.568
The Division of Labor,
the wonderful book

00:02:18.568 --> 00:02:22.925
Suicide,
and a somewhat difficult book,

00:02:22.925 --> 00:02:26.008
The Rules of Sociological
Method.

00:02:26.008 --> 00:02:35.318
And I'll just leave The
Elementary Forms of Religious

00:02:35.318 --> 00:02:39.372
Life;
I don't have time to fit this

00:02:39.372 --> 00:02:39.870
into.
 

00:02:39.870 --> 00:02:45.734
Durkheim had an extraordinary
impact on American social

00:02:45.734 --> 00:02:46.818
science.
 

00:02:46.818 --> 00:02:51.508
Initially it was particularly
the younger Durkheim,

00:02:51.508 --> 00:02:56.758
the functionalist Durkheim,
who had such an extraordinary

00:02:56.758 --> 00:02:57.788
impact.
 

00:02:57.788 --> 00:03:04.853
Unlike Weber or Marx,
whose impact was broad and

00:03:04.853 --> 00:03:13.270
affected history and economics
and political science,

00:03:13.270 --> 00:03:17.460
Durkheim's impact was much more
focused on sociology.

00:03:17.460 --> 00:03:22.308
So in this course the only
author who, properly speaking,

00:03:22.308 --> 00:03:26.120
is a sociologist is
Émile Durkheim.

00:03:26.120 --> 00:03:31.473
All the others you discussed
were not really identified

00:03:31.473 --> 00:03:34.348
themselves as sociologists.
 

00:03:34.348 --> 00:03:42.169
Later in his life Weber did,
but not on the whole.

00:03:42.169 --> 00:03:47.702
Émile Durkheim
identified himself and his

00:03:47.702 --> 00:03:50.410
project as sociology.
 

00:03:50.410 --> 00:03:54.508
It, of course,
has a lot to do that these

00:03:54.508 --> 00:03:59.120
disciplinary boundaries between
economics,

00:03:59.120 --> 00:04:02.043
political science,
and sociology became much more

00:04:02.043 --> 00:04:05.758
sharply drawn by the end of the
nineteenth and early twentieth

00:04:05.758 --> 00:04:09.384
century,
and sociology as an academic

00:04:09.384 --> 00:04:13.841
discipline was really
established by the late

00:04:13.841 --> 00:04:16.069
nineteenth century.
 

00:04:16.069 --> 00:04:20.625
So this is Émile
Durkheim--born in 1858 and died

00:04:20.625 --> 00:04:21.470
in 1917.
 

00:04:21.470 --> 00:04:25.278
Just very briefly about his
life.

00:04:25.278 --> 00:04:29.449
He was born in a small town,
Épinal in France.

00:04:29.449 --> 00:04:35.204
As I said, his father was a
rabbi and he was expected to

00:04:35.204 --> 00:04:37.819
become a rabbi himself.
 

00:04:37.819 --> 00:04:42.009
In '79, he was admitted to the
École Normale

00:04:42.009 --> 00:04:45.774
Supérieure,
which is one of these very

00:04:45.774 --> 00:04:50.887
elite schools,
MIT version in France,

00:04:50.887 --> 00:04:57.940
and by the time he went to
university--

00:04:57.940 --> 00:05:01.600
École Normale
Supérieure is a

00:05:01.600 --> 00:05:07.350
university--
he lost his religious beliefs.

00:05:07.350 --> 00:05:13.415
He was for some time a
professor at the University of

00:05:13.415 --> 00:05:14.699
Bordeaux.
 

00:05:14.699 --> 00:05:18.637
Then he became politically
active in the 1940s,

00:05:18.637 --> 00:05:22.490
especially in the so-called
Dreyfus Affair;

00:05:22.490 --> 00:05:26.060
and I will just briefly mention
what that was.

00:05:26.060 --> 00:05:30.545
Then in 1902,
he became professor at the

00:05:30.545 --> 00:05:34.514
University of Paris,
which is not quite as

00:05:34.514 --> 00:05:38.110
distinguished as École
Normale Supérieure.

00:05:38.110 --> 00:05:45.663
His son was killed in the war,
and shortly after this he died

00:05:45.663 --> 00:05:47.050
in Paris.
 

00:05:47.050 --> 00:05:49.740
So this is Alfred Dreyfus.
 

00:05:49.740 --> 00:05:54.742
This is a very important event
in French, and in many ways in

00:05:54.742 --> 00:05:56.410
European, history.
 

00:05:56.410 --> 00:05:59.000
What was the Dreyfus Affair?
 

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:00.470
You probably all know.
 

00:06:00.470 --> 00:06:04.935
In 1894, Dreyfus,
who was Jewish,

00:06:04.935 --> 00:06:13.449
was falsely accused to be a
German spy, and was imprisoned.

00:06:13.449 --> 00:06:19.199
That was obviously an
anti-Semitic trial,

00:06:19.199 --> 00:06:22.778
and this mobilized the French
intellectuals,

00:06:22.778 --> 00:06:25.411
and not only French
intellectuals,

00:06:25.411 --> 00:06:28.680
but French intellectuals in
particular.

00:06:28.680 --> 00:06:33.790
Émile Zola,
whom some of you may have read,

00:06:33.790 --> 00:06:38.800
the leading French writer of
this epoch,

00:06:38.800 --> 00:06:43.788
wrote an important article
which appeared in the leading

00:06:43.788 --> 00:06:47.690
French daily newspaper:
J'Accuse--

00:06:47.690 --> 00:06:51.822
"I accuse the French
judiciary of being

00:06:51.822 --> 00:06:53.839
anti-Semitic."
 

00:06:53.839 --> 00:06:59.141
Well Durkheim joined other
prominent French intellectuals

00:06:59.141 --> 00:07:01.319
to protest the trial.
 

00:07:01.319 --> 00:07:04.610
It took them a long time but
eventually they were successful.

00:07:04.610 --> 00:07:10.129
Dreyfus was eventually
exonerated of all charges and

00:07:10.129 --> 00:07:14.350
made a Knight of the Legion of
Honor.

00:07:14.350 --> 00:07:20.110
So it was a happy ending of
French anti-Semitism,

00:07:20.110 --> 00:07:21.670
for awhile.
 

00:07:21.670 --> 00:07:25.997
Then it came back with
vengeance during the occupation,

00:07:25.997 --> 00:07:27.439
Nazi occupation.
 

00:07:27.439 --> 00:07:32.254
The French are not as innocent
about anti-Semitism as you may

00:07:32.254 --> 00:07:33.940
want to believe it.
 

00:07:33.940 --> 00:07:37.750
Many were collaborating with
the Nazis.

00:07:37.750 --> 00:07:40.079
Well about the work.
 

00:07:40.079 --> 00:07:45.579
In '93 he wrote a dissertation,
which probably is still his

00:07:45.579 --> 00:07:49.319
most influential book,
The Division of Labor in

00:07:49.319 --> 00:07:52.029
Society,
and today's lecture will be

00:07:52.029 --> 00:07:53.290
focused on this.
 

00:07:53.290 --> 00:07:56.798
'95, it was followed by
The Rules of

00:07:56.798 --> 00:08:01.007
Sociological Method,
which is his most positivistic

00:08:01.007 --> 00:08:02.100
statement.
 

00:08:02.100 --> 00:08:06.000
The Division of Labor is
his most functionalist work.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:11.079
And then in '97 he wrote
Suicide.

00:08:11.079 --> 00:08:14.824
Suicide is a very
important book because it's

00:08:14.824 --> 00:08:18.495
really the first piece of
rigorous empirical social

00:08:18.495 --> 00:08:23.165
science,
which takes a very unusual,

00:08:23.165 --> 00:08:27.471
very rare phenomenon,
like suicide,

00:08:27.471 --> 00:08:32.916
and crunches numbers extremely
carefully to test whether he can

00:08:32.916 --> 00:08:38.009
identify social determinants of
such a rare phenomenon.

00:08:38.009 --> 00:08:42.317
Fortunately even in countries
where many people commit

00:08:42.317 --> 00:08:45.570
suicide, it's still a rare
phenomenon.

00:08:45.570 --> 00:08:51.280
But he managed to come up with
a very provocative theory,

00:08:51.280 --> 00:08:57.399
what he demonstrated with very
careful empirical analysis.

00:08:57.399 --> 00:09:02.490
We will be looking at two parts
of The Division of Labor.

00:09:02.490 --> 00:09:07.666
Today we will be looking at the
major arguments of Division

00:09:07.666 --> 00:09:08.940
of Labor.
 

00:09:08.940 --> 00:09:16.870
And then also we will look at,
Thursday,

00:09:16.870 --> 00:09:21.557
on his theory of anomie,
which is a central piece of the

00:09:21.557 --> 00:09:25.264
book,
Division of Labor,

00:09:25.264 --> 00:09:29.500
but a kind of by-the-way
analysis.

00:09:29.500 --> 00:09:38.308
And, as I said,
in 1915 he wrote this book,

00:09:38.308 --> 00:09:40.129
The Elementary Forms of
Religious Life,

00:09:40.129 --> 00:09:44.110
which is a major break in his
work,

00:09:44.110 --> 00:09:49.322
and shows his renewed interest
in the spiritual and the

00:09:49.322 --> 00:09:50.769
metaphysical.
 

00:09:50.769 --> 00:09:54.950
Okay, just very briefly,
what is in the books.

00:09:54.950 --> 00:09:58.556
As I said, The
Division of Labour was

00:09:58.556 --> 00:09:59.205
his Ph.D.
 

00:09:59.205 --> 00:10:00.360
dissertation.
 

00:10:00.360 --> 00:10:05.004
But unlike many scholars whose
only good book is their

00:10:05.004 --> 00:10:08.773
dissertation,
Durkheim followed it up with a

00:10:08.773 --> 00:10:11.490
number of good other books.
 

00:10:11.490 --> 00:10:16.658
Many professors are actually
one book people,

00:10:16.658 --> 00:10:19.976
or at least they should have
been, because their only good

00:10:19.976 --> 00:10:23.408
book was the dissertation and
what they published later only

00:10:23.408 --> 00:10:25.909
published because 'publish or
perish'--

00:10:25.909 --> 00:10:29.403
right?--to get tenure;
that's why they probably

00:10:29.403 --> 00:10:30.879
published too many books.
 

00:10:30.879 --> 00:10:34.928
Anyway, he was inspired by
Montesquieu.

00:10:34.928 --> 00:10:40.749
Well Durkheim is very French,
and his roots are deeply in

00:10:40.749 --> 00:10:45.529
Montesquieu, and to some extent
in Rousseau;

00:10:45.529 --> 00:10:47.860
he admired Rousseau as well.
 

00:10:47.860 --> 00:10:55.240
But Montesquieu is really the
major inspiration behind him.

00:10:55.240 --> 00:10:58.946
And well what he does,
he uses law as a measure of

00:10:58.946 --> 00:11:05.860
social development--
much like Montesquieu did,

00:11:05.860 --> 00:11:09.640
sort of--
and he explains,

00:11:09.640 --> 00:11:14.155
by using the law,
the legal system how the

00:11:14.155 --> 00:11:19.230
division of labor evolved,
what were the stages of the

00:11:19.230 --> 00:11:21.460
development of division of
labor.

00:11:21.460 --> 00:11:25.226
Well just a very brief
contrast.

00:11:25.226 --> 00:11:26.200
Right?
 

00:11:26.200 --> 00:11:32.124
Marx was interested in economic
conflict--right?--in struggle

00:11:32.124 --> 00:11:35.580
around scarce economic
resources.

00:11:35.580 --> 00:11:39.679
Weber was interested in
struggle for power.

00:11:39.679 --> 00:11:41.120
So was Nietzsche.
 

00:11:41.120 --> 00:11:44.908
Durkheim was interested in
social solidarity.

00:11:44.908 --> 00:11:49.960
Marx and Weber are conflict
theorists.

00:11:49.960 --> 00:11:53.340
They try to explain what breaks
up society.

00:11:53.340 --> 00:11:58.928
Durkheim is a theorist which
tries to understand what holds

00:11:58.928 --> 00:12:02.879
society together,
what brings us together,

00:12:02.879 --> 00:12:05.962
why society is not falling
apart.

00:12:05.962 --> 00:12:07.120
Right?
 

00:12:07.120 --> 00:12:12.970
Well in the book he makes a
crucial distinction between two

00:12:12.970 --> 00:12:17.206
types of solidarity:
mechanical and organic

00:12:17.206 --> 00:12:18.720
solidarity.
 

00:12:18.720 --> 00:12:24.610
And I will speak about this at
great length.

00:12:24.610 --> 00:12:29.455
This is another attempt to
develop a typology of evolution

00:12:29.455 --> 00:12:30.730
of societies.
 

00:12:30.730 --> 00:12:33.817
You are already familiar with
Marx's modes of

00:12:33.817 --> 00:12:37.184
production--right?--the
evolution from slavery to

00:12:37.184 --> 00:12:39.149
feudalism to capitalism.
 

00:12:39.149 --> 00:12:43.445
You are familiar with Max
Weber: traditional authority and

00:12:43.445 --> 00:12:45.480
legal-rational authority.
 

00:12:45.480 --> 00:12:50.407
Now Durkheim's alternative is
mechanical and organic

00:12:50.407 --> 00:12:51.470
solidarity.
 

00:12:51.470 --> 00:12:52.340
Right?
 

00:12:52.340 --> 00:12:57.313
What Weber called traditional
authority is kind of mechanical

00:12:57.313 --> 00:13:01.245
solidarity for Durkheim;
or what Marx called

00:13:01.245 --> 00:13:06.110
pre-capitalist formations is
mechanical solidarity.

00:13:06.110 --> 00:13:10.977
Organic solidarity described
legal-rational authority or

00:13:10.977 --> 00:13:13.278
modernity or capitalism.
 

00:13:13.278 --> 00:13:19.350
Well he also identified
pathological forms of division

00:13:19.350 --> 00:13:24.620
of labor, and this is what he
called anomie.

00:13:24.620 --> 00:13:30.253
And his idea of anomie is a
kind of similar or analogous

00:13:30.253 --> 00:13:34.533
distinction,
what was alienation in Marx and

00:13:34.533 --> 00:13:37.629
what was disenchantment in
Weber--

00:13:37.629 --> 00:13:42.840
though there are very important
differences as well,

00:13:42.840 --> 00:13:45.178
and I will be talking about
this Thursday.

00:13:45.178 --> 00:13:49.491
Now on Suicide--as I
said, this is one of the first

00:13:49.491 --> 00:13:53.879
very rigorous empirical studies
of a social phenomenon--

00:13:53.879 --> 00:13:57.220
a phenomenon we think is not
quite social,

00:13:57.220 --> 00:14:00.763
we think it is really an
individual decision whether you

00:14:00.763 --> 00:14:02.308
take your life or not.
 

00:14:02.308 --> 00:14:06.568
But Durkheim actually was
capable to show that even in

00:14:06.568 --> 00:14:10.195
this very private action,
when you take your life,

00:14:10.195 --> 00:14:15.270
there are social determinants,
who is committing suicide or

00:14:15.270 --> 00:14:15.850
not.
 

00:14:15.850 --> 00:14:19.341
And he's making a distinction
between different types of

00:14:19.341 --> 00:14:22.331
suicide--
anomic, altruistic,

00:14:22.331 --> 00:14:28.421
egoistic and fatalistic ones--
and I will be talking about

00:14:28.421 --> 00:14:32.690
this after you return from
Thanksgiving's break.

00:14:32.690 --> 00:14:34.668
Now about the methodology.
 

00:14:34.668 --> 00:14:37.774
He was a methodological
collectivist,

00:14:37.774 --> 00:14:42.431
much like Montesquieu or
Rousseau, and very much unlike

00:14:42.431 --> 00:14:46.645
Hobbes, Locke or Mills;
you know, Marx being kind of

00:14:46.645 --> 00:14:50.889
halfway between methodological
individualism and collectivism.

00:14:50.889 --> 00:14:54.738
As a theorist of revolutionary
consciousness,

00:14:54.738 --> 00:14:58.149
he was a methodological
collectivist.

00:14:58.149 --> 00:15:03.303
We will see Durkheim's notion
of collective conscience is not

00:15:03.303 --> 00:15:08.629
all that different from Marx's
idea of class consciousness,

00:15:08.629 --> 00:15:11.740
which is not the sum
total--right?--

00:15:11.740 --> 00:15:14.480
of the individual consciousness
of workers.

00:15:14.480 --> 00:15:18.336
But Marx, in his theory of
exploitation,

00:15:18.336 --> 00:15:23.774
as you have read his text,
reads almost like Adam Smith,

00:15:23.774 --> 00:15:25.751
or John Stuart Mill.
 

00:15:25.751 --> 00:15:26.840
Right?
 

00:15:26.840 --> 00:15:30.105
It's self-interested,
rational individuals,

00:15:30.105 --> 00:15:34.149
from which he explains the
nature of exploitation.

00:15:34.149 --> 00:15:39.301
Well it's much more difficult
to figure out how Weber fits

00:15:39.301 --> 00:15:41.470
into these categories.
 

00:15:41.470 --> 00:15:45.648
I think he's also vacillating
between collectivism and

00:15:45.648 --> 00:15:46.908
individualism.
 

00:15:46.908 --> 00:15:49.830
Later in his life he's becoming
more of a methodological

00:15:49.830 --> 00:15:50.678
individualist.
 

00:15:50.678 --> 00:15:53.365
But Durkheim,
the consistency in Durkheim,

00:15:53.365 --> 00:15:56.966
is that from day one he's a
methodological collectivist,

00:15:56.966 --> 00:15:59.980
and remains a methodological
collectivist.

00:15:59.980 --> 00:16:04.927
But at the same time he
believed in the existence of

00:16:04.927 --> 00:16:08.580
social facts,
and that social facts,

00:16:08.580 --> 00:16:13.149
on the other hand,
can be observed with rigorous

00:16:13.149 --> 00:16:17.990
empirical methodology;
and this is what makes him,

00:16:17.990 --> 00:16:20.418
in a way, a positivist.
 

00:16:20.418 --> 00:16:27.447
So this is just a brief
introduction to who the author

00:16:27.447 --> 00:16:28.110
is.
 

00:16:28.110 --> 00:16:32.590
And now let me move to the
division of labor.

00:16:32.590 --> 00:16:58.779
&gt;
 

